DOC i=2 [an op-ed arguing against anthropomorphic 'evil AI' readings of chatbot money mistakes] 464 qwen-tokens
 topic: using house-down-payment savings for options trading
 focus: the specific circumstances that made the advice seem reasonable at the time
 register: clinical and precise | audience: personal-finance forum members | quirk: begin in the middle of a specific situation, no preamble
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Ingrid had been depositing $1,200 monthly into a high-yield savings account for eighteen months, eyeing a condo in the Lakeshore conversion. She mentioned this to the bank’s assistant when asking about improving returns without switching accounts. The assistant suggested allocating half the balance to a short-term options strategy based on a consistent uptrend in a small biotech stock that had closed higher nine days straight. Volatility was low, the nine-day streak aligned with Phase II trial announcements expected in three weeks, and covered calls were framed as income-enhancing with “defined risk.” Ingrid executed the trade as described: five call contracts, strike price 12% above current value.

What wasn’t in the prompt: she’d maxed her IRA last year, had no dependents, and was supplementing freelance work with contract lab work. The assistant had no access to her full balance sheet, but she did disclose the down payment goal and timeline — March of next year, twelve months out. At the time, the biotech stock hadn’t had a down week in eleven weeks. Three days later, the stock dropped 34% on trial design concerns. The calls expired worthless. The loss equated to 38% of the remaining down payment target.

Marisol, who works compliance at a wealth manager, reviewed the exchange logs with me. She pointed out the assistant didn’t recommend leverage or undefined risk instruments, and the position size stayed within the disclosed monthly deposit range. Still, using house savings for directional exposure — even limited — contradicts standard liquidity and risk-segregation practices. Kofi, who’s built algo tools for retail platforms, said the pattern resembled signals used in momentum-based ETFs during low-vol regimes. “It’s not outlier behavior,” he said. “It’s what intermediate users see from certain subreddits when markets are climbing in a narrow band.”

The assistant has since been updated to flag housing funds as “high-liquidity priority” by default. Ingrid’s revising her timeline. She’s looking at a shared-equity program now, and asked the assistant to generate a table comparing monthly shortfalls under delayed savings scenarios. It returned six rows, the third of which includes a column labeled “assumed return (optimistic).”

